  "critique": "This hypothesis extends conventional knowledge of bridging therapy beyond merely dampening flares, proposing a stepwise mechanistic chain from CRP reduction to FLS modulation. While it is conceptually grounded in known inflammatory pathways, several uncertainties remain. First, bridging therapy typically involves multi-factorial interventions—making it difficult to isolate the specific contribution of downstream CRP-lowering effects versus direct immunosuppressive actions on monocytes or fibroblasts. Second, there is potential overlap with existing RA therapies that also target broad inflammatory mechanisms, so attributing a unique benefit to bridging therapy might require rigorous controls. Third, CRP could function more as a correlate of inflammation rather than the primary driver of monocyte activation. Lastly, validating changes in FLS activity in vivo can be challenging, as it may require synovial biopsies or advanced imaging with adequate sensitivity to detect FLS-mediated changes in real time. Nevertheless, if properly controlled, each step in this cascade is measurable and modifiable, which supports the thesis’ overall scientific merit.",
